C shouldn't be used as a first language, these days.
The language is perfectly fine, but:
1. There's a lack of documentation that is both up-to-date (C99, latest POSIX standard) and good.
2. C is only good to learn on Unix-like systems. If you don't know Unix yet, this means learning C and Unix at the same time.
I'd recommend newbs learn Python or Java. I first learnt Java, then later learnt C and FreeBSD (Unix) at the same time. Knowing Java and how to program helped me immensely when learning C.

Anonymous Thu 11 Aug 2022 03:30:09 No.50053013 Report
Quoted By:
>>50051311
First of all, I'd argue there are two different skills at play, here.

>Expressive
This is a skill which is directly related to your drawing skill. If you feel your sketches are lifeless, all you have to do is learn to exaggerate their expressions more!

>Interesting and memorable
That's a completely different field, you see. Just because you can draw an expressive wolf doesn't mean you can make me laugh or cry from seeing it. Interest is generally created from character's personalities and development over the course of several drawings, and memorability comes from how you choose to fill in the contextual cracks. A lot of it is in the dynamics between characters who inhabit the same world.

Look, the point I'm trying to make here is that while your drawing skills may have matured, you have neglected focus on your ability to create dialogue, or send a message in a single image, or develop characters. Try starting with an emotional message, or a simple, emotive conversation. Really picture it vividly, and then design your image to wholly serve that basis. That way you exercise the skills you've neglected.
